We have some special puppet openstackism.  Basically this is checking vcpu_pin_set is configured but cpu_dedicated_set is the default.  This should be:

  if $vcpu_pin_set_real and is_service_default($cpu_dedicated_set_real) { ... }

Also historically if we have renamed a var, we'll usually do something like...

if $vcpu_pin_set {
   warning('vcpu_pin_set is deprecated, use cpu_dedicated_set')
}

$cpu_dedicated_set_real = pick($vcp_pin_set, join(any2array($vcpu_pin_set, ','))), $::os_service_default)


then we just set cpu_dedicated_set in the config with whatever the value is. Since we appear to be splitting shared/dedicated, perhaps it makes sense to just take the legacy value and throw it in the dedicated set? I'm not sure what the impact would be.  If not I would just throw warnings/failures for the incompatible logic sets and call it good.

comments aside, couldn't you combine these?

  if $vcpu_pin_set_real != undef {
    nova_config {
      'compute/vcpu_pin_set':      value => $vcpu_pin_set_real;
      'compute/cpu_dedicated_set': value => $cpu_dedicated_set_real;
      'compute/cpu_shared_set':    value => $cpu_shared_set_real;
    }
  }

Since they're effectively doing the same thing, no?

In fact, what's the difference between:

  'compute/vcpu_pin_set':      ensure => absent;

and

  'compute/vcpu_pin_set':      value => $vcpu_pin_set_real;

if

  $vcpu_pin_set_real = undef

? Is the 'ensure' just a safety check?

No, both are doing different things. That's why I have added comments to make is clear for myself as well. 


Here we are checking for condition, when vcpu_pin_set is set,
 but cpu_shared_set is not set. (and since vcpu_pin_set is set, 
we don't need to check for cpu_dedicated_set as both are mutually exclusive.)
so here vcpu_pin_set will take 
  # if vcpu_pin_set is set, but cpu_shared_set not.
  if $vcpu_pin_set_real != undef and $cpu_shared_set_real == $::os_service_default {
    nova_config {
      'compute/vcpu_pin_set':      value => $vcpu_pin_set_real;
      'compute/cpu_dedicated_set': value => $cpu_dedicated_set_real; # assigns service default
      'compute/cpu_shared_set':    value => $cpu_shared_set_real; # assigns service default
    }
  }


Here we are checking if cpu_shared_set and vcpu_pin_set both are set,
and obviously cpu_dedicated_set would not be set and is default.


  # if cpu_shared_set and vcpu_pin_set are set, but cpu_dedicated_set not set.
  if $cpu_shared_set_real != $::os_service_default and $vcpu_pin_set_real != undef {
    nova_config {
      'compute/cpu_shared_set':    value => $cpu_shared_set_real;
      'compute/vcpu_pin_set':      value => $vcpu_pin_set_real;
      'compute/cpu_dedicated_set': value => $cpu_dedicated_set_real; # assigns service default
    }
  }


And regarding difference between both:
1) 'compute/vcpu_pin_set':      ensure => absent;
here we are making sure that it is absent from nova.conf file, since it is deprecated and generally deprecated parameters are default to undef and absent from conf.
But since we have special case, I make sure to add it to conf it it is defined otherwise not.
'compute/vcpu_pin_set':      ensure => absent;

2) 'compute/vcpu_pin_set':      value => $vcpu_pin_set_real;
And it set the parameter value in nova.conf to whatever is the value of vcpu_pin_set_real parameter.

